<HEADLINE>
<P>
CRIMINAL JUSTICE SYSTEM AND PERJURY ON THE WITNESS STAND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It is comforting to see a respected attorney publicly admit what so many have 
privately acknowledged. The police do tell lies. Lies of zealousness, lies of 
omission, lies of cover-up and lies of commission. Worse, these lies are 
condoned, tacitly at least by their supervisors. 
</P>
<P>
An Orange County judge in a traffic court confided that he was aware of the 
lies but that was how the game was played. If an officer had reason enough to 
lie, there was a reason to presume guilt. So much for justice. 
</P>
<P>
Pause, however, to think of the number of times witnesses are influenced, 
coerced and suborned off the stand. Make false identifications, give tainted 
testimony and perjure to please power figures, all in the faith and trust we 
place in police. By the time they reach the stand they believe what they are 
saying well enough to pass any cross-examination. Time indeed for a new look at 
the system. 
</P>
<P>
MAX KRIEGER 
</P>
<P>
Hollywood 
</P>
</TEXT>
